title.narrative: OUTPUT 1.1: DELIVERY OF QUALITY MNCH AND HIV SERVICES

description.narrative: Output 1.1: By 2023, the capacity of the Ministry of Health and the cadre of health workers is improved to deliver quality integrated maternal, neonatal and child health (MNCH) and HIV services., which contributes to Access To Justice, Child Health, Child Health (Covid), Cross-Sectoral Communication For Development, Early Childhood Development, Hiv Prevention, Immunization, Immunization (Covid), Maternal And Newborn Health, Maternal And Newborn Health (Covid), Operations Support To Programme Delivery, Supply And Logistics, Treatment And Care Of Children Living With Hiv. UNICEF aims to achieve this through Advocacy And Public Engagement, Developing And Leveraging Resources And Partnerships, Evaluations, Research And Data, Fostering Innovation And Use Of New Technologies, Operational Support To Programme Delivery, Systems Strengthening And Institution Building. This contributes to the following Country Programme result: Outcome 1:By 2023, young children (0 to 9 years), particularly the most vulnerable, benefit from gender responsive health, nutrition and early learning services.

description.narrative: UNICEF has provided concerted support to the MoH to ensure continuity of essential Reproductive, Maternal, Newborn, Child and Adolescent Health (RMNCAH) services through the report period marred by the worsening Covid19 pandemic situation. However, service disruptions (for many reasons) has resulted in a lower coverage for key interventions compared to 2019. About 6,238 pregnant women received first ANC services between March and May as against 8,835 women during the same period in 2019, while 65% of children received MCV1 (April to June) as against 91% in the corresponding period of 2019. | Status:On-track | As-of Date:31/12/2019
